<font color="#FF0000">VETS AND NON-VETS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct  9 11:05:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I appreciate the responses to my posting, particularly the notable difference in tone from earlier postings.  I can also acknowledge that we will never agree about certain things - those of you who believe that protests against the war prolonged it, those of us who believe that we were a contributing factor in changing the perception of the nation about what was going on in Viet Nam, and therefore changed its course for the better, to the degree that anything about that war could be considered &quot;better&quot;.<br><br>
Isn't interesting that when you disagree with someone, you always assume they must be ignorant of history.  Perhaps it is just that the lessons I draw from history are the not the same as you.  I do not believe that the history of the U.S. military unilaterally reveals a picture of defending rights and freedom, and I would suggest that there are many episodes which reveal the contrary.  The U.S. military often defends the only the interests of those who run the country - the corporate and multinational powers whose business interests frequently drive military actions.  That's history too, like it or not, and democracy has little to do with it. <br><br>
I agree that Viet Nam vets did face rejection when they returned home - I addressed that in my original post, and I wouldn't for a moment defend it or rationalize it.  But in the end, the greatest injustice done to the vets was by the government - the military itself, and the governmental apparatus that to this day refuses to address the injuries to vets that don't fit into the familiar molds, of which dioxin exposure is only one. <br><br>
I don't quite understand this business about baking cookies - you think we were cute little bakers puttering around in the kitchen thinking we were doing good while the real war raged around us, and all we were really doing was using up resources?  I guess my whole point in this dialogue is that it has been a long struggle for me personally to come to the understanding that the majority of the people who actually fought in the war are not necessarily the people responsible for the war - a critical distinction which is easily lost, because, as the old slogan says, &quot;what if we gave a war and nobody came?&quot;  I know that there are many of you out there - a lot of you post here at this site - who still defend the war, blame the protesters for our &quot;loss&quot;, who believe we were right to be in Viet Nam. We will never agree about that.  If I understand you, you fought exactly for our right to have such a fundamental disagreement, absent, I hope,  name-calling and recrimination.  I don't happen to think the war was about fighting for our freedoms here in the U.S. - few wars the U.S. has fought - with WWII being the gigantic exception -  have been fought for our U.S. democratic freedoms, but given that you do, and that you made major sacrifices in that fight, I simply reserve the right to disagree.  This doesn't for a moment mean that I minimize the sacrifices you made, or the price you paid, and that's important.<br><br>
One other thing - do most vets really think that what the anti-war folks were about was being against the people who fought the war rather than the war itself?? Is this a common perception?  NO ONE I ever knew believed that - we may have been angry at those who did fight the war, some of us clearly had a snotty and arrogant view towards soldiers, but that was NEVER what the anti-war movement I was a part of was about.  It was about a different understanding of what those freedoms we've been debating were about and who had the right to determine what freedom meant to whom, and how they acted on it.  You may HATE my definition of democracy and how I run my government, but does that give you the right to napalm me off the earth?  Only apparently if I call myself a communist, because the last century is rife with examples of truly dispicable leaders who called themselves anti-communists and not only got our blessings, but our money and plenty of it.  So the anti-war movement I was a part of, for a lot of years, was about the death and destruction and viciousness of the war, on both sides, on anyone's side - it was against U.S. policies (I am a U.S. citizen, after all) in Southeast Asia, and U.S. military &quot;interventions&quot; where the U.S. had no business being.  Millions of people came to agree with this view, and I can't help but believe that some part of it was also a consideration of what it meant that an entire country, men, women, children, were willing to do what the Vietnamese did to get the U.S. out.  A country united, whether we agree with what they united over or not - and that's a tough one, isn't it?  I won't defend what they did, and I won't argue with you about it, just as what the U.S. isn't defendable.  It was a war, what did we think they would do?  And after all, we had the whole experience of the French in Viet Nam, speaking of history. <br><br>
I hope this dialogue continues, because 30 years later the wounds are obviously still very deep, and we see evidence of that in a whole lot of other ways in the political scene of this country today.  Looking forward to more comments.   <br><br>
Lin<br>

<p><code>--   (Lin) </code><p>


